{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17515875","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17515875"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:57+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:35:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12517"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12517"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.02,0.1,0.45,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5018"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54299"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5018","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5018"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39797"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"3100"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10069"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"16143"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54299","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/54299"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 71-year-old man is admitted to the geriatric unit due to cognitive impairment. His family have noticed a progressive decline in the patient\u0027s short term memory over the last year. They became particularly concerned in the last month as they have found on many occasions his kitchen stove left on, expired food in the fridge and they have noticed his webster pack is not completely empty at the end of the week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes GORD, bipolar disorder, hypothyroidism and well controlled diabetes for which he takes pantoprazole, lithium, thyroxine and metformin XR.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, a MMSE is performed and a score of 10/30 is obtained, with major deficits in orientation and short term recall.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA MRI brain is subsequently requested.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be seen on imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Atrophy of the medial temporal lobes","Evidence of previous infarcts","Atrophy of the frontal lobes","Generalised cortical atrophy","Loss of grey white matter differentiation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis clinical scenario is most consistent with Alzheimer\u0027s disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlzheimer\u2019s disease is the most common form of dementia and typically presents in the elderly population, in patients older than 65 years. It is characterised by progressive decline in cognitive function especially episodic short term memory. Alzheimer\u0027s disease is associated with \u003Cstrong\u003Emedial temporal lobe atrophy on MRI, \u003C/strong\u003Eand these radiological findings can often precede clinical features of the disease. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEvidence of previous infarcts\u003C/strong\u003E would suggest \u003Cstrong\u003Evascular dementia\u003C/strong\u003E, but this is less likely in this patient because he has no underlying comorbidities such as hypertension or cardiovascular disease and his decline has been gradual rather than a \u0027stepwise\u0027 fashion, which would be more in keeping with vascular dementia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELoss of grey white matter differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in ischaemic infarction due to cytotoxic cerebral oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAtrophy of frontal lobes \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be more in keeping with \u003Cstrong\u003Efrontotemporal dementia\u003C/strong\u003E but this is less likely in this patient because he has not had behavioural changes or changes in executive functioning.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGeneralised cortical atrophy\u003C/strong\u003E can be a non-specific sign that is associated with general ageing, and evidence shows pathological changes in medial temporal lobe may precede generalised cortical atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlzheimer\u0027s disease is the most common form of dementia and has established imaging findings which can support a clinical diagnosis. It is however a spectrum with individuals with positive imaging findings still ranging clinically from cognitively normal to mild cognitive impairment and dementia, often progressing over a number of years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe three best validated neuroimaging biomarkers for Alzheimer\u0027s being ; \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E1. Medial temporal lobe atrophy on MRI \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E2. posterior cingulate and temporoparietal hypometabolism on 18FDG-PET as measures of neurodegeneration\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E 3. cortical amyloid \u03b2 deposition on amyloid-PET imaging.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Alzheimer\u0027s disease is associated with medial temporal lobe atrophy on MRI","Alzheimer\u0027s disease is a common form of dementia, with imaging studies playing a role in supporting clinical diagnosis","Alzheimer\u0027s disease is a spectrum in terms of cognitive impairment, from cognitively normal through to mild cognitive impairment and dementia"],"references":["Scheltens P, De Strooper B, Kivipelto M, et al. Alzheimer\u0027s disease. Lancet. 2021;397(10284):1577-1590. doi:10.1016/S0140-6736(20)32205-4","Oldan JD, Jewells VL, Pieper B, Wong TZ. Complete Evaluation of Dementia: PET and MRI Correlation and Diagnosis for the Neuroradiologist. AJNR Am J Neuroradiol. 2021;42(6):998-1007. doi:10.3174/ajnr.A7079"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39797"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12517"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"39797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/39797"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-02T18:27:09+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-02T18:29:04+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5018"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"54299"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"30","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/30"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udff4\u200d\u2620\ufe0f","name":"Radiology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-15T15:37:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"3100","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3100"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Alzheimer\u2019s disease","synonyms":["AD","Alzheimer\u0027s disease","Alzheimer disease"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-09-20T19:32:07+09:30","u